"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapter 26
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-26-26.py

Key decisions:
- v28 already present ("my blood of the covenant, poured out for many") — skipped
- Anointing at Bethany (26:6-13): direct revelation — Jesus accepts worship and
  declares the woman's act as preparation for his burial; "wherever this gospel is
  proclaimed" is a universal Christological claim about his own death's significance
- Last Supper (26:17-29): direct revelation throughout — Jesus institutes the
  eucharist as his own body and blood, the new covenant; v29 (I will not drink
  again) is the eschatological projection toward the kingdom's consummation
- Gethsemane (26:36-46): direct revelation — "not as I will, but as you will" is
  the highest expression of the Son's obedience; the cup = divine wrath (Ps 75:8;
  Isa 51:17; Jer 25:15)
- Arrest (26:47-56): direct revelation — "all this has taken place that the
  Scriptures of the prophets might be fulfilled"; Jesus controls the narrative
- Trial before Sanhedrin (26:57-68): direct revelation — 26:64 is the climactic
  Christological claim: "you will see the Son of Man seated at the right hand of
  Power and coming on the clouds of heaven" — Dan 7:13 + Ps 110:1 combined
- Peter's denial (26:69-75): revelation of God — the predicted denial fulfilled;
  classified as revelation because Jesus' foreknowledge is confirmed and the
  disciple's weakness is the backdrop to grace
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "26": {
    "1": '<p>A direct revelation: "When Jesus had finished all these sayings, he said to his disciples..." The fifth and final closing formula of the Matthean discourses ("when Jesus had finished...") marks the completion of the Olivet Discourse (chs. 24-25) and Jesus\' entire public teaching ministry. The Christological pivot: what follows is not teaching but action — the passion narrative that his entire ministry has been anticipating. The teacher who taught becomes the sacrifice he taught about.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation: "You know that after two days the Passover is coming, and the Son of Man will be delivered up to be crucified." The self-prediction of crucifixion tied to the Passover timing is the Christological foreknowledge of the passion\'s details and schedule. The Son of Man who will be "delivered up" (<em>paradidotai</em>) is the Passover lamb who will be sacrificed at the Passover. The Christological identification of Jesus with the Passover lamb is implicit here and will become explicit in Paul (1 Cor 5:7: "Christ our Passover lamb has been sacrificed").</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the chief priests and the elders of the people gathered in the palace of the high priest, whose name was Caiaphas." The gathering of the Sanhedrin leadership at Caiaphas\'s palace is the human-political side of the passion\'s machinery. The Christological irony: while Jesus is predicting his crucifixion to the disciples, the authorities are meeting to plan it. The two-track narrative — divine foreknowledge and human plotting — will converge at the cross.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "And plotted together in order to arrest Jesus by stealth and kill him." The plot to arrest Jesus by stealth — avoiding the public during the festival — is the political calculation that has been building since 21:46. The Christological bearing: the authorities must work in secret because the public recognizes something in Jesus that the authorities refuse to acknowledge. The crowd\'s protection of Jesus (his popularity) forces the conspiracy underground.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "But they said, \'Not during the feast, lest there be an uproar among the people.\'" The decision to avoid the feast (Passover week) is overridden by Judas\'s offer (v.14-16) — the betrayal provides the covert access that the authorities need. The Christological irony: the very timing they sought to avoid (Passover) becomes the time chosen by the Father for the sacrifice of the true Passover lamb. Human calculation is overtaken by divine economy.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now when Jesus was at Bethany in the house of Simon the leper..." The Bethany setting — two miles from Jerusalem, the home of Mary, Martha, and Lazarus (John 12:1-8 parallels this scene) — is the place of the last recorded act of devotion before the passion. The Christological reception: Jesus receives in Bethany what he will not receive in Jerusalem. The anointing that prepares for death comes from those who love him, not those who will kill him.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation: "A woman came up to him with an alabaster flask of very expensive ointment, and she poured it on his head as he reclined at table." The anointing of the head is the royal anointing — the act by which kings were consecrated in Israel (1 Sam 10:1; 16:13: Samuel anointed Saul and David on the head). The woman who anoints Jesus on the eve of his death is enacting a coronation that the authorities are simultaneously plotting to prevent. The Christ — the Anointed One — receives his anointing.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when the disciples saw it, they were indignant, saying, \'Why this waste?\'" The disciples\' indignation at the extravagance is the economic calculation that misses the Christological significance. The "waste" they see is, from the perspective of the woman\'s love and Jesus\' coming death, the most fitting use of the ointment. The disciples have learned about service and sacrifice but have not yet understood that some expressions of devotion to Christ exceed economic calculation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "For this could have been sold for a large sum and given to the poor." The reasonable alternative — sell and give to the poor — is not wrong in itself (cf. 25:35-36: the poor must be served). The Christological priority: the woman has understood what the disciples have not — that the one present before them is the one through whom all other service is oriented. The anointing of Christ is not an alternative to serving the poor; it is the act that defines the meaning of all service.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus, aware of this, said to them, \'Why do you trouble the woman? For she has done a beautiful thing to me.\'" The "beautiful thing" (<em>kalon ergon</em>, literally "good/beautiful work") is the Christological affirmation of extravagant devotion. The awareness of the disciples\' reaction (before they speak) is the Christological divine perception. The one who commends her act as beautiful is the one who knows its full significance — the anointing of the body before burial.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct revelation: "For you always have the poor with you, but you will not always have me." The saying about the poor is not a dismissal of the poor but a Christological claim about his own uniqueness and temporal presence. The poor will always require service (Deut 15:11: "the poor will always be with you in the land") — that obligation is permanent. But the opportunity to anoint the embodied Son of God before his death is singular. The Christological present tense: he will not always be with them in this form.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A direct revelation: "In pouring this ointment on my body, she has done it to prepare me for burial." The Christological interpretation of the anointing as burial preparation is Jesus\' own reading of the woman\'s act — perhaps beyond her own conscious intention. He receives a royal anointing and reads it as the preparation for the burial that is coming. The one who will be anointed for kingship (the triumphal entry) is about to be anointed for burial. Both are true; the cross is the throne.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct revelation: "Truly, I say to you, wherever this gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what she has done will also be told in memory of her." The promise that the woman\'s act will be told "wherever this gospel is proclaimed in the whole world" is the Christological claim about his own death\'s universal significance. The gospel proclaimed throughout the world (24:14) includes the story of this woman who understood something the disciples did not. Her act of preparation for his death is inseparable from the gospel of his death — the good news is that he died, and she prepared him for it.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A shadow: "Then one of the twelve, who was called Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests." The immediate juxtaposition of Judas\'s departure with the woman\'s extravagant devotion is the Christological contrast of the passion narrative\'s opening: one disciple anoints Jesus for burial in love; another disciple delivers him for execution for money. The "one of the twelve" — the insider status named — is the Christological wound of betrayal by the near, the familiar, the one who ate at the same table.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation: "And said, \'What will you give me if I deliver him over to you?\' And they paid him thirty pieces of silver." The thirty pieces of silver is the fulfillment of Zech 11:12-13 (the shepherd valued at the price of a slave, Exod 21:32, and the money thrown to the potter). The Christological irony: the one who is worth more than many sparrows (10:31), who is the cornerstone rejected by the builders (21:42), is sold for the price of a slave. The transaction that the authorities make exposes their valuation of the Son of God.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A shadow: "And from that moment he sought an opportunity to betray him." The seeking of an opportunity — the conspiracy now activated within the inner circle — is the Christological tragedy of Judas. He has been present for all of Jesus\' teaching and ministry; he was among the twelve sent out with authority (10:1-4). The betrayal is not the act of an outsider but of one who had been given everything and chose to sell it for thirty pieces of silver.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now on the first day of Unleavened Bread the disciples came to Jesus, saying, \'Where will you have us prepare for you to eat the Passover?\'" The disciples\' question about the Passover preparation is the Christological setting of the Last Supper: the Passover meal, the annual memorial of the Exodus from Egypt, will become the occasion for the institution of the new covenant meal that memorializes the new Exodus from sin. The typological structure: Passover lamb (Exodus) is replaced by Passover Lamb (Christ).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said, \'Go into the city to a certain man and say to him, \'The Teacher says, My time is at hand. I will keep the Passover at your house with my disciples.\'\'" The "my time is at hand" (<em>ho kairos mou engys estin</em>) is the Christological announcement of the passion\'s timing: the appointed hour that Jesus has been pointing toward throughout the Gospel has arrived. The same divine timing that governs the mission (cf. John 7:8: "my time has not yet fully come") now arrives. The master of time announces the hour.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the disciples did as Jesus had directed them, and they prepared the Passover." The preparation of the Passover by the disciples at Jesus\' direction is the Christological execution of the divine plan. The disciples who prepare the Passover are preparing the setting for the institution of the new covenant meal — though they do not yet know it. The Passover they prepare will be the last Passover before the reality it pointed to is accomplished.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "When it was evening, he reclined at table with the twelve." The evening Passover meal reclining with the twelve is the Christological gathering of the community before the passion. The "twelve" named — Judas is included — is the Christological precision: the community that gathers around the table includes the betrayer. The table fellowship that Jesus has practiced throughout his ministry (eating with tax collectors, Pharisees, crowds) reaches its climax at this final table.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct revelation: "And as they were eating, he said, \'Truly, I say to you, one of you will betray me.\'" The announcement of the betrayal at the table is the Christological moment of prophetic self-disclosure: Jesus knows who will betray him and names the betrayal before it happens. The "one of you" — addressed to all twelve — is the Christological individual accountability: each must examine himself. The table that offers communion also requires self-examination.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "And they were very sorrowful and began to say to him one after another, \'Is it I, Lord?\'" The sorrow of all twelve and the question "is it I, Lord?" is the Christological invitation to self-examination. Each disciple knows his own potential for failure; none confidently excludes himself. The "Lord" (<em>Kyrie</em>) of the question is the recognition that the one who knows the betrayer is the one before whom each is examined. The table is the place of self-disclosure.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "He answered, \'He who has dipped his hand in the dish with me will betray me.\'" The identification of the betrayer as the table-companion is the Christological fulfillment of Ps 41:9: "Even my close friend in whom I trusted, who ate my bread, has lifted his heel against me." The Psalm quoted by John 13:18 is cited by the pattern here. The intimacy of dipping in the same bowl — the shared meal — makes the betrayal the ultimate violation of covenant friendship.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct revelation: "The Son of Man goes as it is written of him, but woe to that man by whom the Son of Man is betrayed! It would have been better for that man if he had not been born." The "goes as it is written" is the Christological double movement: the death is divinely appointed (Isa 53; Dan 9:26) and the betrayer is personally culpable. The divine necessity does not remove human responsibility. The woe on the betrayer — "better if he had not been born" — is the Christological seriousness about the weight of this act. Both the sovereignty of God and the freedom of Judas are held together.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "Judas, who would betray him, answered, \'Is it I, Rabbi?\' He said to him, \'You have said so.\'" The Christological confirmation — "you have said so" (<em>sy eipas</em>) — is the same formula Jesus will use with Pilate (27:11) and the high priest (26:64). It is neither a denial nor a full confession but the turning of the question back on the asker. Judas has identified himself by his own words. The "Rabbi" (teacher) rather than "Lord" (Kyrie) of the other disciples is the Christological distance in Judas\'s address: he does not call him Lord.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "Now as they were eating, Jesus took bread, and after blessing it broke it and gave it to the disciples, and said, \'Take, eat; this is my body.\'" The institution of the Eucharist — took, blessed, broke, gave — is the fourfold eucharistic action repeated from the feeding miracles (14:19; 15:36). The "this is my body" (<em>touto estin to sōma mou</em>) is the Christological identification of the bread with his physical person. The act of giving the bread is the act of giving himself — the self-offering that the cross will complete is here enacted in anticipation.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "And he took a cup, and when he had given thanks he gave it to them, saying, \'Drink of it, all of you..\'" The command "drink of it, all of you" is the Christological universality of the cup\'s offering — not some but all. The cup that represents his blood is available to every disciple at the table. The Christological grace: the one who will pour out his blood for many opens the cup to all who will receive it. The exclusive becomes inclusive at the table the Son sets.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "I tell you I will not drink again of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father\'s kingdom." The eschatological projection — "until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father\'s kingdom" — is the Christological promise that the Last Supper is not the final supper but the penultimate one. The new drinking in the Father\'s kingdom is the consummation of what the eucharist anticipates: the full presence of the risen Son with his people in the new creation. The Passover that began in Egypt will end in the kingdom.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when they had sung a hymn, they went out to the Mount of Olives." The Passover hymns (the Hallel, Ps 113-118) sung at the conclusion of the meal carry the Christological weight of the Psalms\' praise: the one who sings "I will not die but live, and tell of the works of the LORD" (Ps 118:17) is about to die. The Mount of Olives — where the Transfiguration prefigured glory (17:1-8) and the Olivet Discourse anticipated the parousia — is the setting for Gethsemane, where the passion begins.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus said to them, \'You will all fall away because of me this night. For it is written, \'I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered.\'\'" The citation of Zech 13:7 ("strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered") is the Christological self-identification as the shepherd who will be struck. The shepherd imagery is YHWH\'s own (Ezek 34: "I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep"), and Jesus, who has called himself the good shepherd (John 10:11), now identifies with the shepherd struck by the divine sword. The scattering of the disciples will fulfill the prophecy.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "But after I am raised up, I will go before you to Galilee." The resurrection prediction attached to the passion prediction is the Christological pattern of every passion announcement in Matthew: death and resurrection are inseparable. "I will go before you to Galilee" is the promised re-gathering after the scattering (v.31) — the shepherd struck will be raised and will re-gather the scattered sheep. The resurrection is not a postscript but the resolution of the passion.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "Peter answered him, \'Though they all fall away because of you, I will never fall away.\'" Peter\'s confident self-exception — "I will never fall away" (<em>ego oudepote skandalisthēsomai</em>) — is the Christological irony of one who does not yet know himself. The Christological bearing: the one who confessed "you are the Christ, the Son of the living God" (16:16) will deny knowing the Christ three times within hours. The gap between Peter\'s self-confidence and his actual condition is the human condition that grace must fill.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said to him, \'Truly, I say to you, this very night, before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times.\'" The precise prediction — this very night, before the rooster crows, three times — is the Christological foreknowledge of Peter\'s specific failure. The specificity is not cruel but compassionate: Jesus names the denial before it happens to prepare Peter for what comes after it. The one who predicts the denial also says "I will go before you" (v.32) — the denier will be received back.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "Peter said to him, \'Even if I must die with you, I will not deny you!\' And all the disciples said the same." All twelve make the promise; all twelve will break it (v.56: "all the disciples left him and fled"). The Christological instruction in human frailty: the disciples who make the most fervent promises of fidelity are those who have not yet been tested by the Gethsemane darkness. The gap between the table\'s vow and the arrest\'s flight is the gap that only resurrection can bridge.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus went with them to a place called Gethsemane, and he said to his disciples, \'Sit here, while I go over there and pray.\'" The Gethsemane prayer — the deepest exposure of the Son\'s relationship with the Father before the passion — is introduced by the command to "sit here while I pray." The Christological separation: even the disciples cannot enter the innermost space of the Son\'s prayer. The prayer is the Son\'s private dialogue with the Father in the hour of the cross\'s approach.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "And taking with him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, he began to be sorrowful and troubled." The taking of Peter, James, and John — the Transfiguration inner circle — into the Gethsemane vigil is the Christological inverse of the Transfiguration: on the mountain, they saw his glory; in the garden, they witness his agony. "Began to be sorrowful and troubled" (<em>ērxato lupeisthai kai adēmonein</em>) is the full human suffering of the incarnate Son — genuine emotional anguish before the approaching cup.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then he said to them, \'My soul is very sorrowful, even to death; remain here, and watch with me.\'" The "my soul is very sorrowful, even to death" (<em>perilypos estin hē psychē mou heōs thanatou</em>) echoes the language of Ps 42:5, 11 and 43:5 (the psalms of the soul cast down, crying out to God). The Christological depth: the Son of God at Gethsemane is the embodiment of the Psalms\' anguish — the genuine human experience of facing death in fellowship with the Father. The request to "watch with me" is the Son\'s need for human companionship in his darkest hour.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "And going a little farther he fell on his face and prayed, saying, \'My Father, if it be possible, let this cup pass from me; nevertheless, not as I will, but as you will.\'" The Gethsemane prayer is the Christological summit of obedience: the genuine human will ("let this cup pass from me") submitted to the divine will ("as you will"). The cup of divine wrath (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17; Jer 25:15-29) that the Father asks the Son to drink is not evaded but embraced. The "not as I will" is the Son\'s voluntary surrender to the cross — the free act that makes the atonement genuinely voluntary.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he came to the disciples and found them sleeping. And he said to Peter, \'So, could you not watch with me one hour?\'" The sleeping disciples — "could you not watch with me one hour?" — is the Christological loneliness of Gethsemane: the inner circle cannot sustain even an hour of wakefulness with him. The one who will drink the cup of wrath alone finds his companions asleep. The Christological bearing: the passion is ultimately borne alone, because no human companion could enter the space where the Son faces the Father\'s judgment in the sinners\' place.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: "Watch and pray that you may not enter into temptation. The spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak." The watchfulness-and-prayer command is the Christological teaching embedded in the rebuke: the disciples\' sleep is not malice but weakness. "The spirit is willing, but the flesh is weak" is the Christological diagnosis of human limitation — the same disciples who vowed to die with him cannot stay awake. The prayer that sustains the willing spirit against the weak flesh is the prayer the Son himself is modeling.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "Again, for the second time, he went away and prayed, \'My Father, if this cannot pass unless I drink it, your will be done.\'" The second prayer — "if this cannot pass unless I drink it, your will be done" — is the Christological deepening of submission: the first prayer asks if there is another way; the second accepts that there is not. The "your will be done" is the Lord\'s Prayer\'s petition (6:10) prayed by the one who instituted it, in the moment when it costs everything. The Son who taught "your will be done" now demonstrates what it costs to pray it.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: "And again he came and found them sleeping, for their eyes were heavy." The disciples\' continued sleep — eyes heavy — is the Christological solidarity of human weakness: the body\'s demand overrides the spirit\'s intention. The one who prays in the darkness returns twice to find them sleeping. The isolation of Gethsemane is complete: the Father\'s cup must be drunk alone, because no human companion can remain awake through the night of the passion\'s approach.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of God: "So, leaving them again, he went away and prayed for the third time, saying the same words again." The third prayer — "the same words" — is the Christological persistence in the face of the unanswered-from-the-human-perspective prayer. The cup will not pass; the Father\'s will stands. The three prayers mirror the three denials Peter will make within hours — the Son prays three times in submission; the disciple denies three times in fear. The contrast is the measure of the difference between the Son and the failing disciple.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then he came to the disciples and said to them, \'Sleep and take your rest later on. See, the hour is at hand, and the Son of Man is betrayed into the hands of sinners.\'" The "the hour is at hand" (<em>hē hōra ēngiken</em>) is the Christological announcement of the passion\'s beginning. The "hour" that Jesus has been pointing toward throughout the Gospel (cf. John 2:4; 7:30; 8:20; 12:23, 27) has arrived. The Son of Man who predicted his betrayal (26:2, 24) now announces its imminent fulfillment. The prayer is complete; the arrest is coming.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A direct revelation: "Rise, let us be going; see, my betrayer is at hand." The "rise, let us be going" is the Christological voluntary movement toward the arrest. Jesus does not flee, hide, or wait to be found; he moves toward the approaching betrayer. The passive "delivered up" of the passion predictions becomes the active "let us go" of the actual moment. The Son submits to the Father\'s will not by staying still but by going forward to meet it.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of God: "While he was still speaking, Judas came, one of the twelve, and with him a great crowd with swords and clubs, from the chief priests and the elders of the people." The crowd with swords and clubs — a show of force against one man at prayer — is the Christological contrast of power and vulnerability. The armed crowd sent by the chief priests and elders comes for the Son of God, who has just prayed "your will be done." The force of the arrest is the ironic excess of those who fear the one they are arresting.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A shadow: "Now the betrayer had given them a sign, saying, \'The one I will kiss is the man; seize him.\'" The kiss of betrayal is the Christological perversion of the greeting: the kiss of friendship becomes the sign of identification for arrest. In the ancient world, the kiss was the sign of intimate relationship (cf. Prov 27:6: "faithful are the wounds of a friend, but deceitful are the kisses of an enemy"). The betrayal uses the form of love to accomplish its opposite.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A shadow: "And he came up to Jesus at once and said, \'Greetings, Rabbi!\' And he kissed him." The "Greetings, Rabbi!" with the kiss is the Christological double-faced moment: the public greeting, the private signal. The "Rabbi" — teacher, not Lord — is Judas\'s last address to Jesus. The one who has been with Jesus throughout the ministry greets him with a word of honor and the gesture of intimacy while handing him over to the armed crowd.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said to him, \'Friend, do what you came to do.\'" The "Friend" (<em>hetaire</em>) — the same address used to the uncommitted in 20:13 and 22:12 — is the Christological last word of Jesus to Judas: not condemnation but the name for those who are in proximity but not in genuine relationship. "Do what you came to do" is the Christological sovereignty over the betrayal: Jesus does not resist, does not call it off, does not expose Judas to the crowd. He permits what the Father has appointed.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A revelation of God: "And behold, one of those who were with Jesus stretched out his hand and drew his sword and struck the servant of the high priest and cut off his ear." Peter\'s sword-drawing (identified as Peter in John 18:10) is the misguided defense that Jesus immediately counters. The Christological rebuke that follows (v.52) shows that violent resistance is not the way of the kingdom, even when the one being arrested is the Son of God.</p>',
    "52": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then Jesus said to him, \'Put your sword back into its place. For all who take the sword will perish by the sword.\'" The "put your sword back" is the Christological refusal of violent self-defense. The maxim — "all who take the sword will perish by the sword" — is the Christological principle of the kingdom\'s non-violent character. The same one who said "do not resist the one who is evil" (5:39) refuses to resist his own arrest. The kingdom advances not through violence but through the cross.</p>',
    "53": '<p>A direct revelation: "Do you think that I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?" The rhetorical question — twelve legions of angels at his disposal — is the Christological demonstration of the voluntary nature of the passion. He could stop the arrest; he chooses not to. The twelve legions (72,000 angels) available on request is the measure of the submission: the one who has unlimited divine protection available chooses to drink the cup instead of calling for rescue.</p>',
    "54": '<p>A direct revelation: "But how then should the Scriptures be fulfilled, that it must be so?" The "how then should the Scriptures be fulfilled?" is the Christological hermeneutic of the passion: the cross is not an accident but the fulfillment of what the Scriptures required. The Son who knows the Scriptures better than anyone submits to the arrest because the Scriptures have spoken. The fulfillment of prophecy is not fate imposed on a passive victim but the active obedience of the Son who knows what the Father required.</p>',
    "55": '<p>A direct revelation: "At that hour Jesus said to the crowds, \'Have you come out as against a robber, with swords and clubs to capture me? Day after day I sat in the temple teaching, and you did not seize me.\'" The Christological exposure of the arrest\'s absurdity: they treated the temple teacher as if he were a violent criminal, requiring an armed force in the night. The contrast — daily public teaching versus covert nighttime arrest — is the Christological indictment of the authorities\' bad faith. They knew where he was; they chose the cover of darkness.</p>',
    "56": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "But all this has taken place that the Scriptures of the prophets might be fulfilled.\' Then all the disciples left him and fled." The "all this" fulfilled in the Scriptures is the Christological reading of the passion: every element of the arrest — the betrayal, the sword-drawing, the fleeing disciples — is within the prophetic script. And then: "all the disciples left him and fled." The scattering of the sheep (v.31: Zech 13:7) is fulfilled. The Son faces the passion alone, as the Scriptures required and as the Father appointed.</p>',
    "57": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then those who had seized Jesus led him to Caiaphas the high priest, where the scribes and the elders had gathered." The Sanhedrin gathered at the high priest\'s house — in the middle of the night during Passover — is the Christological irregularity of the trial: the urgency of their timing violated their own legal procedures. The gathering of the scribes and elders is the institutional response to the one who has overturned their tables and condemned them with woes. The trial is predetermined; the arrest simply begins the final execution of the plan.</p>',
    "58": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Peter was following him at a distance, as far as the courtyard of the high priest, and going inside he sat with the guards to see the end." Peter following "at a distance" is the Christological description of compromised discipleship. He has not fled like the others (v.56) but he is not inside with Jesus either. "To see the end" — he does not yet know what the end will be. The distance between Peter and Jesus in the high priest\'s courtyard is the geography of the coming denial.</p>',
    "59": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now the chief priests and the whole council were seeking false testimony against Jesus that they might put him to death." The seeking of false testimony by the Sanhedrin is the Christological indictment of the entire trial: they begin with the verdict and seek evidence to support it. The established legal principle (Deut 17:6; 19:15: two or three witnesses required) is being subverted. The Son is condemned not by legal process but by the determination of those who have already decided to kill him.</p>',
    "60": '<p>A revelation of God: "But they found none, though many false witnesses came forward. At last two came forward." The inability to find false testimony — "they found none" — is the Christological irony of the perfect life being subjected to false accusation. The one who has lived perfectly according to Torah cannot be falsely accused consistently; the witnesses contradict each other (Mark 14:56: "their testimony did not agree"). At last, two witnesses are found for the one charge that will serve.</p>',
    "61": '<p>A revelation of God: "And said, \'This man said, \'I am able to destroy the temple of God, and to rebuild it in three days.\'\'" The misquotation of John 2:19 ("destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up") is the Christological garbling of the resurrection prediction. Jesus said "you destroy"; they report "I am able to destroy." The three-day rebuilding — which John interprets as the resurrection of his body — is the charge that will be echoed at the cross (27:40: "you who would destroy the temple"). The false witness accidentally identifies the true sign Jesus offered.</p>',
    "62": '<p>A direct revelation: "And the high priest stood up and said, \'Have you no answer to make? What is it that these men testify against you?\'" Caiaphas\'s question in the face of Jesus\' silence is the Christological fulfillment of Isa 53:7: "he was oppressed, and he was afflicted, yet he opened not his mouth; like a lamb that is led to the slaughter, and like a sheep that before its shearers is silent." The suffering servant is present in the high priest\'s court. The silence before accusation is the silence of the innocent lamb.</p>',
    "63": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus remained silent. And the high priest said to him, \'I adjure you by the living God, tell us if you are the Christ, the Son of God.\'" The high priest\'s oath-adjuration — "by the living God" — is the Christological moment of forced disclosure: the Sanhedrin invokes the divine name to compel Jesus to answer. The question "are you the Christ, the Son of God?" is the question that has been developing throughout the entire Gospel. Under oath before the living God, Jesus will answer.</p>',
    "64": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus said to him, \'You have said so. But I tell you, from now on you will see the Son of Man seated at the right hand of Power and coming on the clouds of heaven.\'" The climactic Christological confession: "you have said so" affirms the identification, and the addition of Dan 7:13 (Son of Man on the clouds) + Ps 110:1 (seated at the right hand of Power) is the dual citation that claims both the divine judge\'s eschatological role and the enthronement at the Father\'s right hand. The one being condemned declares his own future exaltation. The trial\'s verdict cannot stop what he announces.</p>',
    "65": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then the high priest tore his robes and said, \'He has uttered blasphemy. What further witnesses do we need? You have now heard his blasphemy.\'" The tearing of robes (the high priest\'s sign of distress at heard blasphemy) is the Christological recognition that the claim has been heard and found unacceptable. The "blasphemy" verdict is the verdict on the Son of God\'s own self-identification. The one who could only be condemned for claiming what he actually is has finally spoken directly, and the Sanhedrin condemns it as blasphemy.</p>',
    "66": '<p>A revelation of God: "What is your judgment?\' They answered, \'He deserves death.\'" The Sanhedrin\'s death verdict on the blasphemy charge is the Christological judicial irony: they are right that blasphemy deserves death, but the charge of blasphemy is false — Jesus is exactly who he claimed to be. The verdict that condemns him is the verdict that the resurrection will overturn. The judges who pronounce death on the Son of God will see the Son of Man "coming on the clouds of heaven" (v.64).</p>',
    "67": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then they spit in his face and struck him. And some slapped him." The spitting and striking — the violation of the condemned man before execution — is the Christological fulfillment of Isa 50:6: "I gave my back to those who strike, and my cheeks to those who pull out the beard; I hid not my face from disgrace and spitting." The Servant who does not flinch from the spittle and blows is the one before whom the mockers will one day fall. The present humiliation is the Christological valley before the eschatological mountain.</p>',
    "68": '<p>A revelation of God: "Saying, \'Prophesy to us, you Christ! Who is it that struck you?\'" The mocking demand to "prophesy" is the Christological irony at its deepest: the one who has just predicted the Son of Man\'s coming on the clouds of heaven, who predicted the disciples\' flight and Peter\'s denial, who predicted Jerusalem\'s destruction and the end of the age — is asked to perform a parlor trick of identifying his attacker. The blindfolded (Luke 22:64) prophet is the one who sees all. The mockers do not know what they are mocking.</p>',
    "69": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now Peter was sitting outside in the courtyard. And a servant girl came up to him and said, \'You also were with Jesus the Galilean.\'" The servant girl\'s identification of Peter — "you also were with Jesus the Galilean" — is the Christological test of public allegiance. The one who vowed to die with Jesus (v.35) is being asked by a servant girl to acknowledge the connection. The "also" suggests she has identified others; Peter is in a chain of identification that he is about to break.</p>',
    "70": '<p>A revelation of God: "But he denied it before them all, saying, \'I do not know what you mean.\'" The first denial — "I do not know what you mean" — is the evasion before the explicit lie. Peter does not say "I do not know him" yet; he claims incomprehension. The Christological bearing: the denial moves from evasion to explicit lie to sworn denial — a progression that mirrors the way compromise escalates under pressure.</p>',
    "71": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when he went out to the entrance, another servant girl saw him and said to the bystanders, \'This man was with Jesus of Nazareth.\'" The second identification — at the entrance, by another servant girl to bystanders — forces Peter into the public square of denial. The "with Jesus of Nazareth" is the specific association: not just a follower of a teacher but a member of the specific Galilean\'s entourage that has disrupted Jerusalem all week.</p>',
    "72": '<p>A revelation of God: "And again he denied it with an oath: \'I do not know the man.\'" The second denial — "with an oath" — escalates the Christological rejection: Peter invokes divine witness to his claim that he does not know Jesus. The same Peter who confessed "you are the Christ, the Son of the living God" (16:16) now swears an oath that he does not know the man. The descent from confession to oath-denial is the measure of untested faith under pressure.</p>',
    "73": '<p>A revelation of God: "After a little while the bystanders came up and said to Peter, \'Certainly you too are one of them, for your accent betrays you.\'" The Galilean accent that betrays Peter is the Christological evidence that ties him to the Galilean teacher. The speech that identifies him as one of Jesus\' company is the ironic fulfillment: Peter\'s voice, which has confessed Jesus as the Christ, now identifies him as a follower even as his words deny it. The body witnesses what the mouth denies.</p>',
    "74": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he began to invoke a curse on himself and to swear, \'I do not know the man.\' And immediately the rooster crowed." The third denial — with self-cursing and swearing — is the fullest betrayal of the Christological confession. The invocation of curse is the opposite of the beatitudes. And then: the rooster crow. The Christological precision of the prediction fulfilled — exactly as Jesus said, at exactly the moment Jesus said. The denial did not catch Jesus by surprise; he named it before it happened.</p>',
    "75": '<p>A revelation of God: "And Peter remembered the saying of Jesus, \'Before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times.\' And he went out and wept bitterly." The remembering of Jesus\' word is the Christological moment of conviction: the word Jesus spoke at the table is fulfilled, and Peter knows it. The bitter weeping is the Christological response to having denied the one he loves — not the despair of Judas (27:3-5: he hanged himself) but the grief that will become the foundation for the restoration that the Risen Lord will offer (John 21:15-19). Peter\'s tears are the beginning of the road back.'
  }
}

